{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2013}} {{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2013}} {{Underlinked|date=August 2013}} }}
{{Infobox NZ Legislation |short_title = Consumer Guarantees Act |long_title = |introduced_by = |date_passed = |royal_assent = 20 August 1993 |commencement = 1 April 1994 |amendments = |related_legislation = |status = Current }}
The '''Consumer Guarantees Act''' ('''CGA''') '''1993''' was a significant improvement of consumer protection in [[New Zealand]] over its predecessor The Sale of Goods Act 1908, and rectifies a lot of its shortcomings.
== Differences over the Sales of Goods Act== One of the CGA's biggest changes was that it now extended protection to consumers for the supply of services, and not just for purchases of goods under the old Act. Another change was that the CGA explicitly outlawed a merchant from contracting out of the CGA, such as having a "no refunds" or "no returns" displayed.
== Guarantees for goods == The CGA gives guarantees to free title, quality, fitness for purpose and price of consumer goods. The goods must also comply with description and with sample. If a good is [[Fault (technology)|faulty]], the Act gives the retailer a reasonable time to either fix or replace the goods, otherwise the consumer has the right to reject the goods, cancel the contract, and obtain a full refund from the retailer. The [[legislation]] has now been amended to include online purchases, including auction websites as [[Trademe]].<ref>http://www.trademe.co.nz/help/657/consumer-guarantees-act-1993</ref>
== Guarantees for services == The CGA gives guarantees of reasonable care and skill, of fitness for purpose, of completion, and of price for [[consumer services]] supplied.
== Shortfalls of the CGA == While the CGA was a significant improvement over the SGA, the CGA does not apply to either commercial goods, or consumer good or services supplied for business purposes.
